BAFANA Bafana’s failure to qualify for the 2021 African Cup of Nations (Afcon) finals and the 2022 Fifa World Cup has not dampened the spirit of Safa president Danny Jordaan. He feels they’ve achieved some of their targets of Safa’s Vision 2022, as he blows his organisation’s horn. Vision 2022, launched in 2014, was about the rebuilding of Safa structures at all levels to create the conditions that will bring about the sustained international success of our national teams. There were 13 technical performances to establish grassroots football programmes, increase fun element in the sport, establish a strong school sport programme and establishment of provincial, regional, and local high performance centres, National Academy. This is to become the centre of Elite Football Development for the African continent, become number one in Africa at all age group levels, and qualify for the Fifa and continental competitions at all levels. Jordaan said while it was a disaster not qualifying for the Afcon and World Cup finals, they have achieved other goals such as Banyana Banyana qualifying for the World Cup in 2019 for the first time and Bantwana, the SA Under-17 side, qualifying for the 2018 World Cup. “What we wanted to do (more) referee training, women’s football, and the national teams must be globally competitive,” said Jordaan in Durban. “What we have done, if you look back now, CONTINUE ON PAGE 14